@Segura_Lab @HJA_Live Lets connects (after the quarter ends)! We did some attribution to the timing and magnitudes of precipitation in that study, too. That model is mostly a gauge-to-flowing-network study, so we don't get into the precip-runoff-storage-release mechanisms.

@WardHydro @HJA_Live Interesting. I wonder how much change you estimate  annually. Some analysis we did for all gauges showed internal annual decreases in runoff ratios; SWE explain much of the variance. We should talk!

@MattBetts11 @HJA_Live Great idea! We simulated about 148-km of river corridor, though only  38-km flows with any regularity. Awesome 'context' to interpret ecosystem processes.@nwisnoski started down this road a bit, but we never integrated the wet/dry data from this model.https://t.co/YlAYz8iXUA https://t.co/TSpTanI7ny

Just how dry was 2017? Check out the red line in the plot below. Winter flowing length was pretty typical, but we see the most contracted network on record! https://t.co/gThMUyJIGr
Crazy spread here, too! Nearly 18-km maximum (1967 & 1982) vs. 8-km in 2017.

How much is accessible from Lookout Creek? The flowing length that is contiguous to the outlet (i.e., no dry streambed between a location at the outlet) is also dropping. We lost ~40-m/yr of contiguously connected habitat. https://t.co/WZXII8A1Ry
+ check out that spread! Maximum of about 31-km of flowing network in 1982 vs. minimum of 16-km in 2017. That's a massive range if you're a fish or salamander.

Ang mga epekto ng nagbabagong klima, tulad ng pagtaas ng temperatura, pagbabago ng pattern ulan, pagtaas ng lebel ng dagat at matinding sama ng panahon, ay direktang nakaaapekto sa mga cultural heritage sites, tradisyonal na kasanayan, at likas na yaman na mahalaga sa kulturang
-----Ang Climate Change Commission (CCC) ay nakikiisa sa pagdiriwang ng National Heritage Month ngayong Mayo, na may temang ‚ÄúHeritage: Change and Continuity.‚Äù
It also highlights the enduring legacies of Filipino traditions amidst rapidly changing national and global contexts.

Pursuant to Presidential Proclamation No. 439, the month-long observance emphasizes the dynamic nature of both heritage and heritage preservation as fields that are constantly changing and innovating.

The CCC emphasizes the need to incorporate the protection and preservation of cultural heritage sites in climate change action plans, promote sustainable practices and ensure the preservation of our cultural heritage for future generations, even in the face of a changing climate.

The impacts of climate change, such as rising temperatures, changing precipitation patterns, sea-level rise, and extreme weather events, directly affect cultural heritage sites, traditional practices, and natural resources that are integral to Filipino culture.

The mechanism of Energy System Integration is a method to make the industries utilize their energy more efficiently. With ESI, we can be one step closer to our goal of improving resilience to climate change and reducing GHG emissions.

Energy Systems Integration (ESI) is the process of coordinating the operation and planning of energy systems across multiple pathways and/or geographical scales to deliver reliable, cost-effective energy services with minimal impact on the environment.
Network operation and planning, market design, and regulatory provisions are developed separately, but they need to be changed, and the concept of Energy Systems Integration (ESI) has emerged.
The decarbonization of the system in the industry requires an increasing level of integration between its various components.

According to the International Energy Agency, the energy sector accounts for 73% of global GHG emissions, and the industry is a significant contributor to these emissions. So, we need to commit to decarbonization, especially in this sector.
The topic is related to the Paris Agreement and the Net Zero Emission, especially in the topic of the energy sector and its emissions.
In line with The Paris Agreement and The Net Zero Emissions, transition to sustainable energy was one of the three main discussions raised by Indonesia during the G20 Indonesia summit.

The Net Zero Emissions by 2050 Scenario (NZE) is a normative IEA scenario that shows a pathway for the global energy sector to achieve net zero CO2 emissions by 2050, with advanced economies reaching Net Zero Emissions in advance of others.

The Paris Agreement speaks of the vision of fully realizing technology development and transfer for improving resilience to climate change and reducing GHG emissions. It‚Äôs supported by The Net Zero Emissions movement.
